<br>
<br>
<p>
    Flying in to Osaka is usually your best bet for the cheapeast flight into or our of of Japan. I quickly realized
    upon landing, that the language barrier would be a real issue in this country.  Without the benefit of 
    a latin alphabet, it wasn't even possible to attempt to guess the meaning of signs or words and I couldn't
    just type a word into a translator on my phone. You are completely at the mercy of the google translate app and 
    potentially badly worded english translations on public signage. Thankfully, the airport, like most of Japan, 
    has great transportation options.  A short train ride from the airport and I was close enought to walk to my hotel.
     
    <h5>Osaka Castle <a id="link" href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g14127623-d320970-Reviews-Osaka_Castle-Chuo_Osaka_Osaka_Prefecture_Kinki.html  style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Osaka Castle Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>This was my first stop in Osaka and it is well worth a visit.  I didn't buy a lot of tickets in advance for this trip
    and my ability to enter this castle was one of the casualties of that decision.  Despite not going inside, I was still
    in heaven looking at this thing from the outside.  Be prepared to take lots of pictures and to walk a lot.  The grounds
    are huge!</p>
    <h5>Downtown Shopping District <a id="link" href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298566-d1407290-Reviews-Shinsekai-Osaka_Osaka_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Downtown Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>I only spent a day in Osaka.  This was enough to visit the Castle and walk around the downtown shopping district.
    Just these two activites takes up the whole day. I didn't end up buying anything, but this downtown area was
    so much fun just to walk through! It is a window shoppers dream.</p>
</p>
