<br>
<p>
    <h5>Gion Corner <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298564-d324291-Reviews-Gion_Corner-Kyoto_Kyoto_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Gion Corner Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>I spend a few hours here walking around.  I found the streets charming and the architecture fascinating.  There are several
        old school Japanese theaters that I would have loved to catch a traditional Japanese play at but tickets were sold out so
        that is something that should be bought in advance if you are interested. You will most likely see a Geisha or two 
        walking around this area which just adds to the experience.
    </p>
    <h5>Shimogamo-Jinja Shrine <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298564-d1198391-Reviews-Shimogamo_Jinja-Kyoto_Kyoto_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Shimogamo-Jinja Shrine Reviews</a></h5>
    <p> Per Wikipedia, "One of the oldest Shinto shrines in Japan, Shimogamo Shrine is one of a pair alongside Kamigamo Shrine that was constructed in the sixth and seventh centuries in order to protect against malign influences.  
        One of seventeen UNESCO World Heritage Sites in Kyoto, the shrine complex is surrounded by the Tadasu no Mori forest that shelters visitors in a world of green and winding streams as well as a small shrine used to pray for beauty. "
    </p>
    <h5>Imperial Palace <a href= https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298564-d321088-Reviews-Kyoto_Imperial_Palace-Kyoto_Kyoto_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Imperial Palace Reviews</a></h5>
    <p> Per Wikipedia, " is the former ruling palace of the Emperor of Japan. Since the Meiji Restoration in 1869, the Emperors have resided at the Tokyo Imperial Palace, while the preservation of the Kyoto Imperial Palace was ordered in 1877."
    </p>
    <h5>Ninjo Castle  <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298564-d321408-Reviews-Nijo_Castle-Kyoto_Kyoto_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Ninjo Castle Reviews</a></h5>
    <p> Per Tripadvisor, "One can visit various temples in Kyoto but the ultimate is to visit Nijo Castle. This amazing compound was built in 1603 by the Tokugawa Ieyasu a very powerful shogun. The compound consists of three distinctive 
        area, Ninomaru Palace, the Honmaru compond and the garden area."
    </p>
    <h5>Nishiki Market <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298564-d554672-Reviews-Nishiki_Market_Shopping_District-Kyoto_Kyoto_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Nishiki Market Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>Per Japan-Guide.com, "Nishiki Market (錦市場, Nishiki Ichiba) is a narrow, five block long shopping street lined by more than one hundred shops and restaurants. Known as "Kyoto's Kitchen", this 
        lively retail market specializes in all things food related, like fresh seafood, produce, knives and cookware, and is a great place to find seasonal foods and Kyoto specialties, such as Japanese 
        sweets, pickles, dried seafood and sushi."
    </p>
    <h5>Fushimi Inari Shrine and hike <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298564-d321456-Reviews-Fushimi_Inari_taisha_Shrine-Kyoto_Kyoto_Prefecture_Kinki.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Fushimi Inari Temple Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>
        Easily one of my favorite places in Japan!! The shrine itself is amazing. Tons of cool venders abound as you walk up to the
        shrine itself.  So many cool things to look at and interesting smells to take in.  After walking around the main shrine,
        the hike begins.  The view at the top is beautiful along with the sense of accomplishment when you make it to the summit.
    </p>
</p>
