<p>
    <h5>Hida Kokubunji Temple <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298113-d4064168-Reviews-Hida_Kokubun_ji_Temple-Takayama_Gifu_Prefecture_Tokai_Chubu.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Hida Kokubunji Temple Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>Per Wikipedia, "Hida Kokubun-ji (飛騨国分寺) is a Shingon-sect Buddhist temple in the city of Takayama, Gifu, Japan. It is one of the few surviving provincial temples established by Emperor Shōmu during the Nara period (710 – 794). 
        Due to this connection, the foundation stones of the Nara period pagoda located on temple grounds were designated as a National Historic Site by the Japanese government in 1929."
    </p> 
    <h5>Historic Sanmachi Suji  <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298113-d320175-Reviews-Sanmachi_Suji-Takayama_Gifu_Prefecture_Tokai_Chubu.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Historic Sanmachi Suji Reviews</a></h5>
    <p>Per tripadvisor.com, "Three quaint streets comprise this popular neighborhood, tastefully dotted with alluring sake breweries, museums and miso shops."
    </p> 
    <h5>Yoshijima Heritage House <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298113-d3154259-Reviews-Yoshijima_Heritage_House-Takayama_Gifu_Prefecture_Tokai_Chubu.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Yoshijima Heritage House Reviews</a></h5>
    <p> I stumbled upon this gem walking throught the street so Takayama. It's an older home in the traditional Janapese style.  I loved the history it this house.
    </p> 
    <h5>Hida Folk Village <a href=https://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g298113-d320154-Reviews-Hida_Minzoka_Mura_Folk_Village_Hida_no_Sato-Takayama_Gifu_Prefecture_Tokai_Chubu.html style="font-size: 15px; color:darkgray">Hida Folk Village Reviews</a></h5>
    <p> Per Japan-Guide.com, "Hida Folk Village (飛騨の里, Hida no Sato) is an open air museum exhibiting over 30 traditional houses from the Hida region, the mountainous district of Gifu Prefecture around Takayama. The houses were built during the 
        Edo Period (1603 - 1867) and were relocated from their original locations to create the museum in 1971."
    </p>
